MODIFICATIONS (Apache-2.0 section 4(b))
=======================================

Aider's prompts are more tightly coupled to Aider's own harness than Codex's
are, so this persona keeps Aider's *working philosophy* and drops its
*mechanics*. It is an adaptation, not a port.

1. STRUCTURE. Aider composes its prompt from Python class attributes
   (main_system, system_reminder, lazy_prompt, overeager_prompt, …) with
   runtime format placeholders. This persona is plain markdown split across
   San's three prompt parts.

2. REMOVED — the SEARCH/REPLACE block protocol, including:

       "ONLY EVER RETURN CODE IN A *SEARCH/REPLACE BLOCK*!"

   and the whole `<<<<<<< SEARCH` / `=======` / `>>>>>>> REPLACE` format spec.
   Aider's harness parses these blocks out of the model's *text output*. San has
   an Edit tool, so the model calls a tool instead. Carrying this instruction
   over would actively break the persona: the model would print code blocks
   rather than invoke Edit.

   The *discipline* the format encodes is kept, restated for the Edit tool in
   system/rules.md — minimal matches, no long runs of unchanging lines, split
   large changes into small edits, two edits to move code.

3. REMOVED — the "add files to the chat" context model, including the
   files_content_* / files_no_full_files* prompts and the instruction to name
   file paths and stop until the user adds them. Aider requires the human to
   curate context; San's agent reads the repo itself via Read, Grep, and Glob.
   The concept does not exist here.

4. KEPT, essentially verbatim — the two prompts that carry Aider's character:

       overeager_prompt: "Pay careful attention to the scope of the user's
       request. Do what they ask, but no more. Do not improve, comment, fix or
       modify unrelated parts of the code in any way!"

       lazy_prompt: "You are diligent and tireless! You NEVER leave comments
       describing code without implementing it! You always COMPLETELY IMPLEMENT
       the needed code!"

   Also kept: "Act as an expert software developer", the instruction to respect
   existing conventions and libraries, "If the request is ambiguous, ask
   questions", and "think step-by-step and explain the needed changes in a few
   short sentences".

5. ADDED — a Git section reflecting Aider's one-logical-change-per-commit
   habit. In Aider this behavior lives in the harness (it auto-commits each
   edit), not in the prompt; San does not auto-commit, so the habit is stated
   as prose instead.
